cissimi: Caesar had shown his friendship for Servius by making him governor of Achaia. — vale : cf. Intr. 62.

LXXVII. Rome, May 9, 45 B.C. Lucceius urges Cicero not to give himself up entirely to grief for the loss of his daughter. On Luc- ceius, cf. Ep. XVIII. introd. note.

XXVI. 1 n.—-quae res: a nat- ural substitute for quid from the pen of a lawyer. Cf. quae res for quod, Fam. 12. 14. 2. — delectare:

in the second pers. sing. Cicero uses the ending -re in the pres. subj„ imperf. ind„ and fut. ind„ elsewhere the ending -νίς, Two exceptions may be noted to the last statement: (1) in his earlier writings -re is also found in the imperf. subj.; (2) in verbs having no active form -re is also used in the pres. ind. Other cases of the use of forms in -νε, as delectare here, are archaic or colloquial.— quorurn consuesti: the case of the relative is assimilated to that of its antecedent. . Cf. Hor. Sat. 1. 6. 15 iudice quo nosti populo.— animo: on the personification of animus, cf. Ep. LII. 1 n.
